Text: This week was mostly spent figuring out the structure of the project and how each of the different parts of the project will connect together, as part of working on the proposal.

It seems we are still unsure of what language exactly the parser is going to be in but I think the team is thinking of having it as a python script that checks the servers directory for new CSV files to parse every so often.

We know for sure that we will be having a PHP web page with a map on it, could be OpenStreetMaps but Roro is heavily leaning towards Leaflet.js which I'm fine with, and we also know that we will have a MySQL database.
So to host the PHPÂ  pages and the MySQL database we will need a server which luckily my COSC349 paper has a lab on this for week 4 but it's available to read through now.

After trying to arrange a regular time with both clients we found out that Kuku won't be available for this as time spent in meetings with us will cost Eric money, so we can only have meetings with Eric which will be interesting to work around different time zones.
Kuku said he would still be available for technical advice though which is nice.
Eric has been giving us a lot of useful information and seems quite involved with helping us find data sources and advice on what he thinks will be useful.

We arranged a survey to have Eric fill out to help us sift through some of the MSHA data and what he actually wants to keep from it since it has a lot of irrelevant columns and he was quick to fill out that.

It was interesting seeing the work Roro has done so far for the project and making maps with markers on it, using a lot of technologies I haven't seen before which has made me feel like I'm still quite out of date with my knowledge so I'll have to make an effort to talk to him and ask questions about the things that he is using so expand my knowledge base some more.
I spent some time working through the COSC349 lab about setting up an AWS server and some of the AWS tutorials on setting up a LAMP server with a MySQL database instance.
I haven't quite finished these tutorials, I was slowed down a fair bit by picking up a nasty cold.

I'm not sure the current tutorial I'm working through will give us the result I'm looking for as it seems to suggest that there will be a DB instance that can only be connected to by a web page on the EC2 server that sits on the same private cloud.
So I'm not sure if we'll need to connect to the database outside of that using the parser file.
Which may work if it is stored on the EC2 server.
Still some testing to be done there once I've finished this tutorial but if that doesn't work there are other options for tutorials on different setups that should get the job done.
